{"key":"processedPost-14562097","value":{"id":14562097,"first":14557846,"last":14610747,"when":1307245098,"utime":"06/05/11 06:38 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>HorizonSpawn said:</b><br />I used 5% by dry volume of grains: 10 cups of dry rye berries and 4 onces of gypsum. RR, in more recent years has stated that this amount is unnecessary. IIRC; he mentioned (at one point) that 2~3% by volume is about right... He went on to say that a little to much shouldn't hurt anything; but that below 2~3%, the benefits are insignificant.<br /><br />At 2.5%; that would be two ounces, or four tablespoons.<br /><br />Cheers <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/wink.gif\" alt=\":wink:\" title=\":wink:\"/><br /></blockquote><br /><br />You're confusing grains with bulk substrates.&nbsp; Those are the measurements of gypsum for manure, coir, straw, sawdust, etc.&nbsp; For grains, use less.&nbsp; In the old days when we'd just dump a cup of dry grains into a jar and then fill it with water to just even with the top of the grains and PC, we'd add a pinch of gypsum between our thumb and forefinger to each jar as shown in the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Rye-Grass-Seed-Preparation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">rye grass seed preparation video</a>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Now that we've developed much better procedures which involve rinsing and soaking the grains, use a bit more gypsum, but still not even half as much as we'd use for a bulk substrate.&nbsp; Using more is wasteful, but won't necessarily screw up the grains.<br />RR","title":"Re: Grain TEK Inquiry"}}